Question: I was working on a code snippet to get all substrings from a given string.

Here is the code that I use

```
 var stringList = new List<string>();
 for (int length = 1; length < mainString.Length; length++)
 {
    for (int start = 0; start <= mainString.Length - length; start++)
    {
       var substring = mainString.Substring(start, length);
       stringList.Add(substring);
    }
 }

```

It looks not so great to me, with two for loops. Is there any other way that I can achieve this with better time complexity.

I am stuck on the point that, for getting a substring, I will surely need two loops. Is there any other way I can look into ?

Answer:

 The current approach of using two nested loops to achieve this has a time complexity of O(n^2), which isn't optimal, especially when you're dealing with large strings. 

A more efficient way to achieve this without compromising too much on the time complexity involves using a combination of arrays and string concatenation could be as follows:

Instead of building the `substring` using `Substring`, you can concatenate the `substring` using `Append`.

Here is the updated code:

```csharp
var stringList = new List<string>();
for (int length = 1; length < mainString.Length; length++){
    var substring = mainString.Append(mainString, length);
    stringList.Add(substring);
}
```

This approach reduces the need for multiple string concatenations in each iteration, thereby improving the time complexity.

